+### Payload Conventions
+
+Every event keeps the top-level envelope stable and stores event-specific data
+under `payload`. Payload objects use camelCase fields and follow this minimal
+convention so editor hooks, AI work steps, and runtime gameplay code remain
+readable through JSONL, CLI, and API read paths:
+
+```json
+{
+  "kind": "editor-action",
+  "eventType": "selection.changed",
+  "summary": "Unity selection changed.",
+  "status": "completed",
+  "attributes": {
+    "objectCount": 1,
+    "targetPath": "Scene/Main Camera"
+  }
+}
+```
+
+Required payload fields:
+
+- `kind`: one of `editor-action`, `ai-work-step`,
+  `runtime-gameplay-event`, `tool-command`, or `gateway-signal`.
+- `eventType`: dotted or snake_case event name, stable enough for filters.
+- `summary`: redacted human-readable summary for AI context.
+
+Optional payload fields:
+
+- `status`: `started`, `completed`, `failed`, `cancelled`, or another
+  producer-specific state when needed.
+- `attributes`: event-specific scalar or structured values after redaction.
+  Nested arrays and objects are valid JSON values and must be encoded as JSON,
+  not flattened into strings, so CLI/API readers can preserve numbers,
+  booleans, nulls, lists, and object fields.
+
+Producers should avoid duplicating raw secrets, source code, or full gameplay
+state in `attributes`; store hashes, counts, identifiers, or redacted summaries
+instead. Readers must decode `payload.attributes` as JSON values instead of a
+string-only map.
+
